{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515688"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:33:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:33:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12484"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12484"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.09,0.01,0.01,0.71]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4991"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50841"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4991"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36081"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"496"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"4756"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44959"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50841"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents in the clinic with a three day history of severe right sided ear pain and associated discharge. He has had previous similar episodes and these resolved after using medications given to him by his general practitioner. He denies any history of hearing loss, tinnitus or vertigo. He is a swimmer and swims daily in a pool and then uses cotton swabs to clean his ears regularly. He has no history of any allergies or immune system disorder. On examination his right ear canal is erythematous and oedematous with thick, yellowish discharge. The tympanic membrane is not visible due to the swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"After ear toilet, which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral amoxicillin-clavulanate","Clotrimazole drops","Oral naproxen","Oral prednisolone","Ciprofloxacin-dexamethasone drops"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with signs and symptoms of otitis externa, as assessed by the pain and the presence of thick yellowish (purulent) ear discharge. Before antibiotics are considered for this bacterial infection, ear toilet must be performed to facilitate direct action of the treating agent on the infected and inflamed tissues. The best treatment option for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Eciprofloxacin-dexamethasone drops\u003C/strong\u003E, the antibiotic helps in eliminating the bacterial infection while the steroids helps to reduce the inflammation and swelling in the ear canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case because otitis externa is a localised infection and topical treatment is usually enough for treating the infection. Use of oral antibiotics can have systemic side effects and is unnecessary in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClotrimazole drops\u003C/strong\u003E are used in fungal infections. There is no evidence of fungal infection in this patient. The key clinical differentiator between a fungal and bacterial infection is a normal external auditory canal size with copious white patches and occasional visible fungus debris.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral naproxen\u003C/strong\u003E could help in relieving the pain in this patient, but it will not address the underlying issue, which is a bacterial infection and without using any antibiotic it could lead to further complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated because it is not effective for treating otitis externa and can have possible systemic side effects. Oral corticosteroids are reserved for severe inflammation that is not responding to topical treatments.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Combination of antibiotics-steroid drops is the treatment of choice for otitis externa."],"references":["Wiegand S, Berner R, Schneider A, Lundershausen E, Dietz A. Otitis Externa. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2019 Mar 29;116(13):224-234. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.2019.0224. PMID: 31064650; PMCID: PMC6522672."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12484"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36081"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-18T09:05:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-18T09:06:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4991"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50841"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/